<dl id="n08059e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08059e">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08059e"> 59(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> O lay by the fat for to / grease the priest&apos;s boots <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n08059e"><li>FW 176.17 </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/lexg.htm#n08059e">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/l39g.htm#n08059e">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n08059e">MS BL 47471b-51v</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:334 <a name="g10d" href="../../FF/fdra/gda.htm#g10d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/g/g10d.htm#n08059e">Draft: I.7&sect;1.0</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">In the country boots were greased, and goose grease being the most fashionable and highly thought of was used by the clergy. An old ballad began: &ldquo;<mark>Oh! lay by the fat to grease the priest&apos;s boots</mark>.&rdquo; <small> <a name="II8jan24" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#II8jan24"><cite title="source">Irish Independent</cite></a> (8 January 1924) 6/5</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
